      "tier3": "Solar panels work through the photovoltaic effect.  This effect describes the creation of voltage or electric current in a material upon exposure to light.  Solar panels are made of many individual photovoltaic cells, which are typically made of silicon. Silicon is a semiconductor; it's neither a good conductor nor a good insulator of electricity.  Within each cell, a p-n junction is created by doping silicon with different impurities – phosphorus to create an n-type layer (with extra electrons) and boron to create a p-type layer (with electron holes). When sunlight strikes the cell, photons excite electrons in the n-type layer, causing them to move across the p-n junction into the p-type layer. This movement of electrons creates a direct current (DC) electricity.  Multiple cells are wired together in series and parallel to create a solar panel, increasing the voltage and current output.  An inverter is then typically used to convert the DC electricity into alternating current (AC) electricity, which is the type of electricity used in homes and businesses."
